			<h1 align="center">Attributes</h1>
			<hr>
			<h2>&#9758; What are attributes?</h2>
			<p><strong>Attributes</strong> provide additional information about an element. They are special words used inside the <b><i>start tag</i></b> to control the element's behaviour. An <strong>attribute</strong> either modifies the default functionality of an element type or provides functionality to certain element types unable to function correctly without them.</p>
			 <div class="note">
				 <p><strong>Remember:</strong> All <strong>HTML</strong> elements can have attributes.</p>
			</div>
			<h2>&#9758; Basic Attribute Types</h2>
			<div class="background">
				<ul style="list-style-type:square">
					<li><strong><i>Required Attributes</i></strong></li>
						<p>Needed by a particular element type for that element type to function correctly.</p>
					<li><strong><i>Optional Attributes</i></strong></li>
						<p>Used to modify the default functionality of an element type.</p>
					<li><strong><i>Standard Attributes</i></strong></li>
						<p>Supported by a large number of element types.</p>
					<li><strong><i>Event Attributes</i></strong></li>
						<p>Used to cause element types to specify scripts to be run under specific circumstances.</p>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<h2>&#9758; Syntax</h2>
			<p><strong>Attributes</strong> usually come in name/value pairs, such as <b><i>name="value"</i></b>.</p>
			<p>The <b><i>name</i></b> is the property you want to set and <b><i>"value"</i></b> is what you want the value of the property to be set and always put within double quotes.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>Example</strong>: &lt;a href=&quot;planet.html&quot;&gt; or &lt;h1 align="center"&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<h2>&#9758; Global Attributes</h2>
			<p>The following global attributes can be used on <strong>any</strong> HTML element:</p>
			<div class="example">
				<ul style="list-style-type:square">
					<li><b>acceskey</b></li>
					<li><b>class</b></li>
					<li><b>contenteditable</b></li>
					<li><b>data-*</b></li>
					<li><b>dir</b></li>
					<li><b>draggable</b></li>
					<li><b>dropzone</b></li>
					<li><b>hidden</b></li>
					<li><b>id</b></li>
					<li><b>lang</b></li>
					<li><b>spellcheck</b></li>
					<li><b>style</b></li>
					<li><b>tabindex</b></li>
					<li><b>title</b></li>
					<li><b>translate</b></li>
				</ul>
			</div>
			<p>&#10145; If you would like to know more about each global attribute mentioned above click <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/tags/ref_standardattributes.asp">here</a></p>
			<h2>&#9758; Useful HTML attributes</h2>
			<h3>HTML href Attribute</h3>
			<p>For &lt;a&gt; and &lt;area&gt; elements, the href attribute specifies the URL of the page the link goes to.</p>
			<p>For &lt;base&gt; elements, the href attribute specifies the base URL for all relative URLs on a page.</p>
			<p>For &lt;link&gt; elements, the href attribute specifies the location (URL) of the external resource.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>&lt;a&gt; Example</strong>: &lt;a href=&quot;your URL goes here&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;area&gt; Example</strong>: &lt;area shape=&quot;rect&quot; coords=&quot;0,0,82,126&quot; href=&quot;whatever.htm&quot; alt=&quot;Whatever&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;base&gt; Example</strong>: &lt;base href=&quot;your URL goes here&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;link&gt; Example</strong>: &lt;link rel=&quot;stylesheetwhatever&quot; type=&quot;text/css&quot; href=&quot;whatevertheme.css&quot;&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML src Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>src</strong> attribute instructs the browser where on the server it should look for the object thatâ€™s to be presented to the user. This may be an object in the same directory, an oject somewhere else on the same server, or even an object stored on another server.</p>
			<h4>Elements which applies to:</h4>
			<ul style="list-style-type:square">
				<li>&lt;audio&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;embed&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;iframe&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;img&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;input&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;script&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;source&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;track&gt;</li>
				<li>&lt;video&gt;</li>
			</ul>
			<div class="example">
				<p></p>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML width Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>width</strong> attribute specifies the width of the element, in pixels.</p>
			<p></p>
			<div class="example">
				<p></p>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML heigth Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>height</strong> attribute specifies the height of the element, in pixels.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p><strong>&lt;img&gt; Example</strong>: &lt;img src=&quot;yourimage.gif&quot; alt=&quot;Your Image&quot; height=&quot;50&quot; width=&quot;50&quot;&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;object&gt; Example</strong>: &lt;object data=&quot;example.swf&quot; height=&quot;200&quot; width=&quot;200&quot;&gt;&lt;/object&gt;</p>
				<p><strong>&lt;embed&gt; Example</strong>: &lt;embed src=&quot;example.swf&quot; width=&quot;100&quot; height=&quot;100&quot;&gt;</p>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML alt Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>alt</strong> attribute provides alternative information for an image if a user for some reason cannot view it (because of slow connection, an error in the src attribute, or if the user uses a screen reader).</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p></p>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML lang Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>lang</strong> attribute specifies the language of the element's content. Common examples are "en" for English, "es" for Spanish, "fr" for France and so on.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p></p>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML title Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>title</strong> attribute specifies extra information about an element.</p>
			<p>Since the title attribute is part of the <strong>Global Attributes</strong>, it can be used on <strong>any</strong> HTML element you wish.</p>
			<div class="example">
				<p></p>
			</div>
			<h3>HTML style Attribute</h3>
			<p>The <strong>style</strong> attribute specifies an inline style for a particular element. It will override any style set globally, such as styles specified in the <b><i>&lt;style&gt;</i></b> tag or in an external style sheet.</p>
			<p>&#10145; You can find out more about style attributes in the <a href="goes to CSS section">CSS section</a>.</p>
